Future Work
This repository represents the first stage of a larger research effort focused on trustworthy AI evaluation.

Planned future work includes:
Expanding the benchmark beyond the initial pilot.
Evaluating multiple frontier language models.
Incorporating clinical expert validation.
Automating portions of the evaluation pipeline.
Releasing larger open-source benchmark datasets.
Developing AI reliability infrastructure that supports safe deployment in regulated and high impact environments.

Healthcare is the starting point—not because it is the final destination, but because it provides one of the clearest environments for understanding whether AI systems can reliably preserve human intent before they are deployed more broadly.

Limitations
The benchmark is based on a small sample size (20 synthetic clinical cases) and is not intended to represent population level performance.
All evaluation cases are synthetically generated and do not include real patient data or real clinical environments.
The study evaluates a single model (Gemini 1.5 flash) and does not include comparative analysis across multiple LLMs.
All evaluations were performed through manual review using a structured rubric, which may introduce subjectivity despite standardized criteria.
The benchmark focuses specifically on clinical discharge summarization tasks and may not generalize to other healthcare workflows or domains.
The results should be interpreted as an early stage validation of an evaluation methodology, not as a definitive measure of model safety.
The framework does not currently include inter-rater reliability or multiple clinician reviewers, which will be addressed in future iterations.
This work is intended as a research prototype and open source benchmark, not a clinical decision-making system or production deployment tool.



